<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="1844" pageId="8" pageNumber="1842" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[144,1104,1117,1691]" box="[144,271,1117,1141]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1842">
<heading box="[144,271,1117,1141]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="8" pageNumber="1842" reason="5">
<emphasis box="[144,271,1117,1141]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1842">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[144,1104,1117,1691]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1842">
Length from 0.8 (adult male) to 1.1 (subadult female) mm. Without pigmentation. Cuticle with ‘smooth’ granulation. Ocelli absent. PAO broadly elliptical, slightly constricted, longer than width of Ant.I and twice as long as inner unguis length (
<figureCitation box="[975,1088,1221,1245]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="10.[144,211,1210,1232]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,168,1178]" captionTargetId="figure-153@10.[144,1104,168,1178]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 5. Aggressopygus sibiricus sp. nov.: (A,B) furca, anterior (A) and lateral (B) views; (C) maxillary head; (D) tibiotarsus 3; (E,F) labrum, variation; (G) anterior part of the head; (H) apical row of labral setae, ventral view; (I) anterior side of manubrium, specimen from mountainous Shoria." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5195067" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5195067/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="1842">Figure 5G</figureCitation>
). Maxillary outer lobe with 4 sublobal hairs, maxillary palp bifurcate. Labral formula as 4/ 5,5,4. A pair of lateral setae of subapical row tooth-like, with or without apical denticles (
<figureCitation box="[152,297,1316,1340]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="10.[144,211,1210,1232]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,168,1178]" captionTargetId="figure-153@10.[144,1104,168,1178]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 5. Aggressopygus sibiricus sp. nov.: (A,B) furca, anterior (A) and lateral (B) views; (C) maxillary head; (D) tibiotarsus 3; (E,F) labrum, variation; (G) anterior part of the head; (H) apical row of labral setae, ventral view; (I) anterior side of manubrium, specimen from mountainous Shoria." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5195067" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5195067/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="1842">Figure 5E–H</figureCitation>
). Labium with 5 papillae (А–Е), 16 guard setae (including e7), papillae A and B thicker, 3 proximal and 4 basomedian setae present. Hypostomal papilla as common for the family, unmodified. Maxillary head compact, without long lamellae, Lam.6 broad, Lam.1 hidden behind Lam.6, not protruded (
<figureCitation box="[793,903,1412,1436]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="10.[144,211,1210,1232]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,168,1178]" captionTargetId="figure-153@10.[144,1104,168,1178]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 5. Aggressopygus sibiricus sp. nov.: (A,B) furca, anterior (A) and lateral (B) views; (C) maxillary head; (D) tibiotarsus 3; (E,F) labrum, variation; (G) anterior part of the head; (H) apical row of labral setae, ventral view; (I) anterior side of manubrium, specimen from mountainous Shoria." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5195067" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5195067/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="1842">Figure 5C</figureCitation>
). Ventral side of a head with 3 + 3 setae, of which 2 + 2 posterior inserted close together. Ant.1 with 2 ventral sensilla (s) and 2 small basal microsensilla (bms), dorsal and ventral, the former set together with long setaceous microsensillum (
<figureCitation box="[692,809,1508,1532]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="10.[144,211,1210,1232]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,168,1178]" captionTargetId="figure-153@10.[144,1104,168,1178]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 5. Aggressopygus sibiricus sp. nov.: (A,B) furca, anterior (A) and lateral (B) views; (C) maxillary head; (D) tibiotarsus 3; (E,F) labrum, variation; (G) anterior part of the head; (H) apical row of labral setae, ventral view; (I) anterior side of manubrium, specimen from mountainous Shoria." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5195067" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5195067/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="1842">Figure 5G</figureCitation>
), Ant.2 with 3 bms and 1 laterodistal s, Ant.3 with 1 bms and with 6 distal s (including 2 lateral), without additional sensilla. Sensilla on Ant.4 thin and tubular, organites stick-like.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[144,1104,1117,1691]" lastBlockId="9.[212,1172,1283,1689]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="1843" pageId="8" pageNumber="1842">
Ordinary setae of body long and rather sparse. The longest setae on posterior segments of abdomen, furcal subcoxa and basal parts of legs ciliated. Axial chaetotaxy as 10,6/4,4,4(5),4 (
<figureCitation box="[346,460,1667,1691]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="14.[144,211,1685,1707]" captionTargetBox="[160,1087,168,1653]" captionTargetId="figure-1@14.[160,1087,168,1653]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figure 7. Posterior part of abdomen of Aggressopygus sibiricus sp. nov. (A) and Micrisotoma achromata (B). s – sensillum, ms – microsensillum, fa – foil seta, tc – ‘tiny’ seta." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5195071" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5195071/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="1842">Figure 7A</figureCitation>
). Sensillary formula as 4,3/2,2,2,3,5 (s), microsensilla (ms) as 1,0/0,0,1 (
<figureCitation box="[350,463,1283,1307]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="9.[212,279,1171,1193]" captionTargetBox="[212,1172,168,1139]" captionTargetId="figure-201@9.[212,1172,168,1139]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 4. Habitus and chaetotaxy of Aggressopygus sibiricus sp. nov. (A), Aggressopygus armatus sp. nov. (B), and Microisotoma achromata (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5195065" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5195065/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="1843">Figure 4A</figureCitation>
). Tergal sensilla well differentiated, on most tergites shorter and finer than common setae. Medial sensilla on Th.II–III situated in front of p-row, on Abd. I–IV in posterior position. Abd.V with 5 sensilla arranged with 3 dorsal long and slender (al, accp1, accp2), one lateral middle-sized sensilla (accp3) slightly thicker than dorsal, and one ventral (
<figureCitation box="[397,519,1410,1434]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="9.[212,279,1171,1193]" captionTargetBox="[212,1172,168,1139]" captionTargetId="figure-201@9.[212,1172,168,1139]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 4. Habitus and chaetotaxy of Aggressopygus sibiricus sp. nov. (A), Aggressopygus armatus sp. nov. (B), and Microisotoma achromata (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5195065" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5195065/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="1843">Figures 4A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[532,566,1410,1434]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="14.[144,211,1685,1707]" captionTargetBox="[160,1087,168,1653]" captionTargetId="figure-1@14.[160,1087,168,1653]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figure 7. Posterior part of abdomen of Aggressopygus sibiricus sp. nov. (A) and Micrisotoma achromata (B). s – sensillum, ms – microsensillum, fa – foil seta, tc – ‘tiny’ seta." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5195071" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5195071/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="1843">7A</figureCitation>
). Microsensilla thick and long. Macrochaetae long and ciliated, 1,1/3,3,3,4 in number, medial ones on Abd.V 1.3–1.7 times shorter than dens and 4.0–4.7 times longer than inner edge of unguis (
<figureCitation box="[724,836,1474,1498]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="14.[144,211,1685,1707]" captionTargetBox="[160,1087,168,1653]" captionTargetId="figure-1@14.[160,1087,168,1653]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figure 7. Posterior part of abdomen of Aggressopygus sibiricus sp. nov. (A) and Micrisotoma achromata (B). s – sensillum, ms – microsensillum, fa – foil seta, tc – ‘tiny’ seta." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5195071" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5195071/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="1843">Figure 7A</figureCitation>
). Foil setae well differentiated, with a cluster of cilia at the middle of the length. Thirteen foil setae arranged in two transversal rows as 4 + 4 anterior (fa1, fa3, fa5, fa7) and 5 posterior (fp0, fp2, fp4). Foil setae fp4 short. Th.III with 2 + 2 ventral setae.
</paragraph>
